node.text:
Long before we started texting under the table at parties, Georgian ladies were using a much simpler handheld device to send messages across the room: their fans! 

Whether you want to introduce yourself, flirt a bit, or just get that annoying courtier to leave you alone, here’s your instructor Lucy Worsley with some of the key phrases you’ll need in order to learn the secret language of the fan. Remember to pay close attention — there’ll be a vocab test at the end 🤓

node.text:
From the 12th century until the 1600s, new Kings and Queens traditionally processed through the city from the #TowerOfLondon ahead of their coronation at @westminsterabbeylondon, as a great way to assert their power and show themselves off in front of their public.
 
Now it’s your turn! Walk in the steps of royalty along the coronation route from the Tower to the Abbey this Bank Holiday weekend 👑 Find out more and book tickets via the links in our bio.

node.text:
We’ve got exciting news. We’re ready to start reopening the palaces! 🥳

On Thursday 18 June our beautiful gardens at Hampton Court Palace and Hillsborough Castle will reopen to the public. We’ve assembled a top team from across the palaces to run you through the new measures we’ve put in place to ensure we can offer everyone a safe and enjoyable visit.

Meanwhile, our work preparing our other outdoor spaces for reopening continues, with indoor spaces at the palaces to follow in line with the latest advice. We look forward to sharing more updates with you soon.

Follow the link in our bio to find out more about visiting and book your tickets.

node.text: The conservation team are investigating the magnificent ceiling of the Wolsey Closet at #HamptonCourtPalace. For many years, it was thought to be made of a material called leather maché, but it was revealed that this is not the case. The exact date and origin of the ceiling are also a mystery. This detective work will let them choose the best conservation methods in order to conserve this glorious craftwork for another 500 years. 🕵️‍♀️

node.title: Conservation of a Tudor ceiling | Beyond Palace Doors

node.text: How do you make an 18th century chandelier? 🕯️ Part of recent restoration work at #KensingtonPalace included hanging new golden chandeliers in the State Apartments. It has taken four years to complete the chandelier project, in which the items were researched, designed and crafted from scratch, with only one visual record and a few descriptions to go on. The carved and gilded chandeliers now hang in the King’s Drawing Room at Kensington for the first time in nearly two centuries.

node.text:
Here is Queen Victoria’s gold and enamel pocket watch 🕔 It was an 11th birthday gift from her mother and is inscribed with a message from the Duchess to her daughter. Curatorial Assistant Aisha Tahir tells us what the watch reveals about Victoria’s childhood. 
The pocket watch is on loan to #KensingtonPalace from the Harewood House Trust and the 8th Earl of Harewood. 
See the watch on display at Kensington for #Victoria200: http://bit.ly/Victoria200

Welcome to the Tower, HMS Albion and @rmbandservice! ⚓

Today saw the return of one of the #TowerOfLondon’s best-loved traditions: The Ceremony of the Constable’s Dues. 

Assembled on Tower Green, the company of HMS Albion presented the Constable of the Tower General the Lord Houghton with a ceremonial barrel of red wine 🍷

In centuries past when the Thames was busy with trade, the Constable of the Tower was entitled to a portion of the cargo of every ship coming into London. Sadly for present-day Constables this profitable system ended long ago, but the tradition lives on to this day with the Ceremony of the Constable’s Dues!

We’ll be rolling out the barrel at the #TowerOfLondon on Monday 🍷

We’re excited to be welcoming the company of HMS Albion to take part in the return of a historic tradition we last marked in November 2019: the Ceremony of the Constable’s Dues!

Why do we make such a fuss over a barrel of wine? Back when the Tower Wharf and surrounding docks were busy with trading ships, being the Constable of the Tower came with considerable perks. As the person responsible for charging levies on goods coming into the city by river, the Constable was entitled to a portion of the cargo of every ship – his ‘dues’ – which included kegs of rum and wine.

Sadly for present-day Constables we now let Thames traffic pass by the Tower for free, but the tradition lives on with the Constable’s Dues! Once or twice a year we invite a visiting Navy ship to parade their company through the Tower, and present a ceremonial barrel of rum or wine to the Constable on Tower Green. (And don’t worry, we then invite them to The Keys to enjoy the contents of the barrel with us too 🥂)

Join us at the Tower on Monday at midday to witness this centuries-old tradition, and of course stay tuned for updates right here on Instagram.

On 9 September 1087, William the Conqueror died in Normandy.

After famously defeating Harold Godwinson at the Battle of Hastings in 1066, William established himself as King of England, and had the imposing #TowerOfLondon built to defend and assert his royal power 👑

But unfortunately for William, he probably never saw his mighty fortress completed; with his seat on the English throne relatively secure he spent most of his time abroad. In the end, an accident on his horse at the Battle of Mantes finished him off.

The Norman conquest of England had a profound impact on the British Isles, transforming our politics, language and culture in ways still felt today. The Tower is testament to this momentous legacy, standing strong nearly 1,000 years later! 🏰

node.text:
Happy birthday, Elizabeth I 🎂

Born just after 3pm on this day in 1533, Elizabeth’s arrival was met with muted celebrations, as her parents Anne Boleyn and Henry VIII had been hoping for a son. Official letters announcing the birth of a prince were hastily altered, and planned jousts and fireworks were cancelled!

But while baby Elizabeth didn’t get the royal welcome she deserved, she grew up to prove her detractors wrong: today Elizabeth is remembered as one of the most iconic and influential monarchs in English history 👑

📷 A miniature of Elizabeth I in the early years of her reign from around 1560-65, possibly by celebrated portraitist Nicholas Hilliard. Cared for by @royalcollectiontrust.

node.text:
London’s burning! London’s burning!

On 2 September 1666 an “infinite great fire” tore through the City of London. Diarist Samuel Pepys made his way to the #TowerOfLondon to view the blaze from “one of the high places” of the fortress, and wrote about what he saw in his famous diary:

“I did see the houses at that end of the bridge all on fire, and an infinite great fire on this and the other side the end of the bridge […] So down, with my heart full of trouble, to the Lieutenant of the Tower, who tells me that it begun this morning in the King’s baker’s house in Pudding-lane”.

Thankfully, the Tower itself escaped the flames, with the authorities acting quickly to pull down surrounding buildings to create a firebreak. They had good reason to hurry: at the time the Tower was being used to store hundreds of tonnes of gunpowder! 💥

node.text:
On 28 August 1835, the #TowerOfLondon Menagerie opened to the public one last time before closing for good, on the orders of the Duke of Wellington.

Founded by King John in the early 1200s, for over 600 years the Menagerie was home to wild animals gifted to monarchs, including lions, elephants, and even a polar bear!

However, cramped conditions and poor levels of care meant that many animals sadly didn’t survive for long, and after the Menagerie was closed some were transferred to the Zoological Society of London at Regent’s Park, now @zsllondonzoo 🦁

Today at the Tower, the Menagerie is commemorated through wire animal sculptures by artist Kendra Haste.
